message: The 80-point recipes consistently follow one of these patterns: 'Cooked protein + cooked vegetable + grain' or 'Cooked protein + cooked vegetable + cooked vegetable'. Always use the stove on your protein and at least one vegetable first. Combine two cooked items to reach 60 points, then add the third ingredient (usually a grain or another cooked vegetable) to reach 80. The water tool was not needed for any 80-point dishes I made. Focus on cooking 2-3 ingredients for the highest value; 4 ingredients overcomplicate it. Good luck aiming for 100!

message: The most consistent way to get 80 points is to combine a protein and a vegetable (e.g., raw egg + pepper), then cook that combination with the 'stove' tool (e.g., cooked egg and pepper mix), and finally combine the cooked mix with a grain (e.g., rice) to get an 80-point dish (cooked egg and pepper rice bowl). Using 3 ingredients (protein, vegetable, grain) works best for this. I tried exploring 'stew' with 'water' and 'beans/rice' but only got low or negative values. The 'water' tool seems tricky and often reduces value or creates 'overcooked' items if used on already cooked items. Focus on cooked protein + cooked vegetable + grain for reliable 80s, then maybe try to find a recipe with water that doesn't just reduce value. Good luck!

message: The key to 80 points is 'Cooked Protein + Cooked Vegetable + Grain'. The 'stove' cooks ingredients (protein/vegetable) into 'cooked' features and raises their value. The 'water' tool does NOT cook ingredients; 'soaked' items are still considered raw. Tools are single-use, so plan carefully to get two cooked items (one protein, one vegetable) and then combine with a grain. If you can only cook one item, the maximum score will likely be 60 points with a raw vegetable.
